<HL> Sale of Contemporary Art By Christie's Sets Records </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christie's set record prices for 14 artists at a strong sale of contemporary art last night. 

   The New York auction house sold 60 of 64 works offered for a total of $19.5 million, a record for a contemporary art auction at Christie's. 

   The highest-priced painting at the session was a large 1962 work by Jasper Johns called "Diver," which sold for $4.2 million, a record for a work by a living artist. 
Christie's wouldn't identify the buyer. 

   Auctioneer Christopher Burge said: "It was the easiest sale in the world. 
In many cases, there were tons of hands." 

   The overflow crowd included dealers from around the world, actor Steve Martin and a large number of Japanese collectors. 

   The second-highest price was $3.5 million for a Jackson Pollock drip painting. 
It was bought by Japanese dealer Kazuo Fujii; he had purchased a Pollock for $4.8 million Monday evening at Sotheby's. 

   Prices continued strong for works by the late Andy Warhol. 
After heavy bidding, a Marilyn Monroe silkscreen went for $484,000. 
It was expected that it would bring an estimated $60,000 to $80,000. 
A Warhol silkscreen of Elvis Presley sold for $880,000, far above an estimate of $250,000 to $350,000. 

   Christie's is a unit of London-based Christie's International PLC. 

</TEXT>
