<HEAD>88-Year-Old Nominated For Fiction Work</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lowercase `them' in 10th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 88-year-old Spanish immigrant who waited more
than four decades to have his novel published is among nominees for
fiction in the 1990 National Book Awards.
   Felipe Alfau was one of five novelists nominated in the fiction
category. Others included two first-time novelists, Elena Castedo
and Jessica Hagedorn, and writers Charles Johnson and Joyce Carol
Oates.
   The nominations were announced Thursday by the National Book
Foundation, the non-profit organization that sponsors the annual
awards.
   In the non-fiction category, authors were nominated for works
about the Morgan banking family, former President Nixon, American
artist Jackson Pollock and Harold Ickes, a member of Franklin
Roosevelt's cabinet.
   Alfau wrote ``Chromos,'' published by Dalkey Archive Press, in
the 1940s. The book is about the experiences of a group of
Spaniards who move to Manhattan in the 1930s.
   A translator for a New York bank before retiring, Alfau also
wrote the 1936 novel ``Locos: A Comedy of Gestures'' and is the
author of a children's book.
   Castedo, who grew up in Chile and worked at odd jobs while
traveling around the world, was nominated for ``Paradise,''
published by Grove Weidenfeld. The book is about a Latin American
ghetto family.
   Hagedorn, a poet, playwright and commentator for public radio,
wrote ``Dogeaters,'' published by Pantheon Books. Her first novel
explores native tradition and popular American culture colliding in
the Philippines, Hagedorn's homeland.
   Johnson, a professor of English at the University of Washington,
was nominated for ``Middle Passage,'' published by Atheneum
Publishers, about a newly freed slave's voyage on a slave ship
bound for Africa in 1830.
   Oates, who won the National Book Award for fiction in 1970 for
her novel ``them,'' is nominated for ``Because It Is Bitter, and
Because It Is My Heart,'' published by E.P. Dutton-William Abrahams
Books. Her 20th novel is about a young white woman and a black
classmate brought together by a murderous street fight.
   Finalists in the non-fiction category include:
   -Ron Chernow for ``The House of Morgan: An American Banking
Dynasty and the Rise of Modern Finance,'' publisher Morgan Entrekin
Books-Atlantic Monthly Press.
   -Samuel G. Freedman for ``Small Victories: The Real World of a
Teacher, Her Students and Their High School,'' publisher
HarperCollins.
   -Roger Morris for ``Richard Milhous Nixon: The Rise of an
American Politician,'' publisher Henry Holt.
   -Steven Naifeh and Gregory White Smith for ``Jackson Pollock: An
American Saga,'' publisher Clarkson N. Potter.
   -T.H. Watkins for ``Righteous Pilgrim: The Life and Times of
Harold L. Ickes, 1874-1952,'' publisher Henry Holt.
   The two winners will be announced Nov. 27. Each winner receives
a $10,000 check.
</TEXT>
