<HEAD>Museum Bequeathed $60 Million In Modern Art</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Pollock and Schreiber throughout. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Modern art valued at more than $60 million,
including a classic ``drip'' painting by Jackson Pollock, has been
donated to the Museum of Contemporary Art.
   The gift of 18 works by 13 artists is from the estate of Rita
and Taft Schreiber and also includes art by Piet Mondrian, Arshile
Gorky and Joan Miro.
   Schreiber, who died in 1976, was Ronald Reagan's Hollywood press
agent and a member of his ``kitchen cabinet'' when he was governor
of California. Mrs. Schreiber, who died earlier this year, was a
frequent visitor to the museum.
   ``It was my mother's wish that these works of art remain in Los
Angeles where she and my father lived,'' said the couple's
daughter, Lenore Greenberg, MOCA board president.
   The 18 pieces are considered the best of the widely admired
Schreiber collection, said Richard Koshalek, director of the
10-year-old museum.
   ``With these works, we are able to strengthen the foundation of
our museum, providing brilliant historical context for much of the
work being created today,'' he said.
   He said the collection was assembled with ``extraordinary
sensitivity, passion and clear-sighted discipline.''
   The works span from 1930 to the mid-1960s. Predominant among
them is Pollock's ``Number 1,'' a classic ``drip'' painting from
1949.
   Other works include Mondrian's 1939 ``Abstract Painting,'' Mark
Rothko's 1949 ``Yellow and Orange-(Red),'' two versions of Alberto
Giacometti's 1960 sculpture ``Tall Figure'' and his ``Interior
Studio with Three Apples.''
   Also included are Miro's 1949 ``Personnages dan La Nuit,''
Gorky's 1947 ``Betrothal I,'' Pierre Alchinsky's 1960 ``Pres de La
Bete,'' Alexander Calder's 1964 ``Portrait,'' Morris Louis' 1961
``Pillar of Delay'' and Jean Dubuffet's 1962 ``L'Ecoulment De La
Ville.''
</TEXT>
