<HL> Sotheby's Repaints
Art Auction Record
In $18.9                                                                   
Figure Is for Single Session
Of Contemporary Works;
'Pink Lady' Is Top Seller
---
By Meg Cox
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 05/05/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> PLA </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's sold a record $18.9 million of contemporary art at an auction last night. 

   The amount was a record for a single session of contemporary art, far exceeding the previous record of $13.2 million. 
Lucy Mitchell-Innes, head of contemporary art for Sotheby's, said it was a "truly remarkable sale," setting records for 17 artists. 

   The top-grossing lot of the evening was a painting called "Pink Lady" by Willem de Kooning that sold for $3.6 million, including a 10% buyer's commission. 
The painting ties the record for the highest auction price ever for a work of contemporary art, paid for a Jasper Johns painting last fall. 

   The evening's emotional high point came when a Japanese businessman successfully bid for another De Kooning, "Woman", at $2.5 million. 

   The businessman, Morimasa Ohkawa, chief executive officer of a Tokyo real-estate development firm, let out a scream when the auctioneer indicated his bid had won. 
The painting is an abstract, brightly-colored oil depicting a female. 

   The auctioneer, John L. Marion, said: "We've got a satisfied buyer. 
That's what I like." 
Mr Ohkawa said, through an interpreter, that it was his first auction ever and his first acquisition of a contemporary work. 
The interpreter said: "He feels very lucky because the price was much lower than he was prepared to go. 
He was willing to go to $3.5 million." 

   Mr. Ohkawa, wearing a tuxedo, said his private collection includes impressionist art and a great number of traditional Japanese works. 

   The painting was sold by Playboy Enterprises Inc.; it had been expected to bring $1.5 million to $2 million. 
In addition, Playboy sold another of the evening's top-grossing lots, a Jackson Pollock drip painting that went for $2,750,000. 

   Sotheby's is the auction-house unit of Sotheby's Holdings Inc. of London. 

</TEXT>
