<HL> Christie's Sells Painting By Johns for $7 Million </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> U.CHR </CO>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christie's sold a record $37.3 million of contemporary art at an auction last night, with the highest individual price, $7 million, going for a Jasper Johns painting. 

   In the packed sale room, records were set for 25 artists. 
The Johns painting, "White Flag," brought a record price for a work by a living artist. 

   The painting was bought by a private collector from Sweden, Hans Thulin, who said, "I consider this a very exceptional acquisition. 
It reflects my general belief that you can never pay too much for outstanding quality." 
Mr. Thulin said he is the sole owner and chairman of a Swedish real-estate conglomerate, Consolidator-Granaten Group. 

   Four works out of 86 didn't sell, a vast improvement from a sale at Christie's a year ago following the stock-market crash when one in four works didn't sell. 
Martha Baer, a head of 20-century art at Christie's, said most of the buying was done by U.S. collectors and added that the election didn't have any effect on the prices. 
"They were A-plus works by A-plus artists," said Ms. Baer. 

   The first 32 works came from an important collection assembled by Burton and Emily Hall Tremaine. 

   Artists for whom records were set included Jackson Pollock, Mark Rothko, Roy Lichtenstein and Andy Warhol. 

   Christie's is a unit of London-based Christie's International PLC. 

