<HEAD>East Wing Anniversary Show To Feature 20th Century Works</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: Gallery officials, with 1 graf
giving total of works in modern art collection, Brown quote.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Gallery of Art will celebrate the
10th anniversary of its modernistic East Building with a two-year
exhibition of its small but rapidly growing collection of 20th
century art, gallery officials said Tuesday.
   The show, which will open Dec. 4, will include about 250 works by
modern artists ranging from Pablo Picasso to Andy Warhol. It will
occupy more than half of the building's 55,000 square feet of
gallery space on three of its five levels.
   ``The new exhibition will demonstrate our progress in expanding
the gallery's collection of modern art,'' said director J. Carter
Brown.
   About 60 percent of the paintings, sculptures and drawings in the
show will come from the gallery's permanent collection. Half of
those were acquired in the decade since the East Building opened on
June 1, 1978. The remaining works will be on loan from private
collections.
   Curator Jack Cowart said that although the East Building was
designed in part by architect I.M. Pei specifically to house the
gallery's modern art collection, the only permanent exhibition site
for those works has been on the less visible concourse or basement
level of the building.
   Cowart said 20th century art was virtually non-existent at the
National Gallery until the early 1960s, when the gallery received a
gift of about 100 works of modern art from the Chester Dale
collection.
   Since then, he said, the gallery's collection has grown steadily
with the goal of assembling a high-quality range of modern masters,
although there is no pretense of matching the vast numbers of New
York's Museum of Modern Art or Metropolitan Museum of Art.
   ``We acquire carefully, slowly and with great care,'' said
Cowart, who estimated that about 90 percent of the gallery's
acquisitions are gifts rather than purchases.
   Two major gifts were made in 1986, when the gallery acquired more
than 900 drawings and 100 paintings by American artist Mark Rothko
and ``The Stations of the Cross,'' a 15-painting series by Barnett
Newman.
   The gallery's modern paintings, sculptures and decorative art
objects have grown in the past decade from 272 to 613 works,
compared with thousands in other collections. ``Our center of
gravity is the old masters,'' Brown conceded.
   The exhibition opening in December, involving extensive
remodeling of the East Building's gallery spaces, will move 20th
century art upstairs from the basement ``to give the collection a
presence the public can count on,'' Cowart said.
   The tower and upper levels will feature pre-World War II artists
such as Picasso, Henri Matisse, Georges Braque and Amedeo
Modigliani. The concourse galleries will highlight the works of
postwar artists such as Warhol, Newman, Jackson Pollock, Roy
Lichtenstein and Jasper Johns.
   Brown said the exhibition may embark on a national tour once it
closes at the East Building in December 1990.
</TEXT>
