<HEAD>Gallery Showcases Images of Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEWISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan is a mythical centaur. He's
also Rocky, a human television set and a warrior in what is billed
as the first art exhibit to feature a sitting president.
   These images of Reagan by nearly 40 artists, including Andy
Warhol and Red Grooms, appear in an exhibit titled ``Reagan:
American Icon'' at Bucknell University's Center Gallery.
   The show, featuring works done in the past eight years, opened
Jan. 14 and will run through March 23. Reagan will yield the
presidency to George Bush on Jan. 20.
   ``It's unprecedented that a president has had contemporary
artists do this many images of him,'' said Robert P. Metzger, the
gallery's director, who added that the exhibit was the first of its
kind for a president still in office.
   The Reagan interpretations range from flattering to critical, but
Metzger was quick to point out the exhibit was put together based on
the quality of the art, not politics.
   ``You don't go out of your way to offend someone with an art
exhibit, but on the other hand, art is not docile. We do want to
arouse people; we want to make them think,'' he said.
   The show includes:
   _ Two Andy Warhol screenprints of Reagan in Van Heusen shirt
advertisements published during the president's acting days.
   _ A mock wooden toy by Red Grooms showing Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail Gorbachev standing on a missile connected to four
wagon wheels titled ``Nuclear Nuts.''
   _ A heroic depiction of Reagan as a centaur _ half horse, half
man _ by the Moscow-born artists Komar and Melamid.
   _ A ceramic image by Robert Arneson of Reagan as a television
set, the president's smiling face coming out of the screen, a wire
hand as the antenna and a warning on the back: ``Do not expose this
appliance to thought or reason.''
   _ A painting by Israeli-born artist Ori Hofmekler titled ``Ronnie
II'' showing Reagan as the Sylvester Stallone movie character Rocky
Balboa, sporting boxing gloves and shorts and wearing a championship
belt with the presidential seal on it.
   _ A lifelike portrait of Reagan by Leon McFadden, with the
president's face covered by tiny, nearly invisible logos of all of
the Fortune 500 companies.
   The show contains two paintings of Nancy Reagan and one of the
president and first lady together.
   It also has books, articles, posters, photographs, buttons,
T-shirts and postcards about the Reagans culled from Metzger's
personal collection of 50,000 books and 50 filing cabinets filled
with memorabilia about celebrities ranging from Marilyn Monroe to
the artist Jackson Pollock.
   Metzger said he conceived the idea for the show several years ago
but did not think enough work with Reagan as the subject would exist
until at least 1991.
   To find the work, Metzger quizzed museum directors, talked to
artists and went to galleries in New York City.
   ``It was just detective work tracking down the material,'' he
said. ``When I began the search I didn't know there was enough for a
show. I was sort of groping. Who would have guessed?''
   Metzger, who has a doctorate in art history from the University
of California signed by Reagan when he was California's governor,
said the show is historically significant because it is done by
artists while Reagan was still in office.
   ``This will be a show that will be a watershed,'' he said.
``There's probably no other show at any other museum devoted to one
person. There just isn't the material.''
   Even though almost all of the images of Reagan depict him in his
role as president, it was Reagan's former life as an actor which
attracted the artists, Metzger said.
   ``I do think it's this duality of his life. ... It's captured the
imagination of a lot of contemporary artists,'' he said.
</TEXT>
