<HEAD>Note Engraver and Painter Dead at 86</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The painter and engraver William Stanley Hayter,
who taught his innovative printmaking techniques to such renowned
artists as Pablo Picasso and Salvador Dali, is dead at age 86.
   Hayter died of cardiac arrest Wednesday in Paris, where he had
been a leading figure in the art scene since the 1920s.
   The International Herald Tribune said Friday that Hayter was
credited with turning engraving into a lively and experimental form
that attracted many famous artists to his studio in Montparnasse.
   Among those visiting the studio he called Atelier 17 were
Alexander Calder, Marc Chagall, Jackson Pollock, Dali and Picasso.
   Hayter was born in London in 1901 and graduated from Kings
College, London, with honor degrees in art and chemistry. He worked
in Iran from 1922 to 1925 for the Anglo-Iranian Oil Co., but his
first interest was art.
   ``My father was a painter, and (so were) a lot of people in my
family before, so I was messing about with painting fairly
seriously when I was a child,'' he once said. ``I was painting all
the time when I was in the (Middle) East. I didn't do much with
prints until I came to Paris.''
   He discovered the vanishing art of original printmaking and
revolutionized it with new techniques, including a method of color
printing from a single plate instead of using a separate plate for
each tone.
   Hayter wrote two books that are essential reading for print
makers: ``New Ways of Gravure'' (1949) and ``About Prints'' (1962).
   He lived in Paris from 1926 to 1939, when he moved his studio to
the New School in New York and gave impetus American printmaking.
He returned to Paris in 1950.
</TEXT>
