   New York -- Imagine that you have a very wealthy and
perspicacious old aunt and that she has a garage full of
memorabilia from the 1940s. This includes not only paintings
and sculptures, but Tupperware containers, chairs designed by
famous architects and artists, industrial objects (such as a
giant propeller blade from the St. Regis Paper Company),
streamlined household objects (including elegant old
typewriters and watches), photographs by famous photographers
of equally famous writers and scientists, and even a bright
red Cisitalia 202 GT sports car designed by Pinin Farina.
   Some aunt. Some garage.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Well, the aunt in this case is one of New York's most
visible grande dames, the Museum of Modern Art. And the
garage is the grande dame's basement, which doubles as her
special exhibition space. The show is called "Art of the
Forties," and like the decade to which it is dedicated, it is
at once wonderful and awful. Wonderful because it is such a
hodgepodge, and awful for exactly the same reason.
   Although this exhibition focuses on the variety of
artistic expression during what was arguably the most
tumultuous decade of our tumultuous century, this is not an
"idea" or theme show. In fact, any ideas that creep in seem
to do so more or less by accident. Instead some 300 objects
of varied shapes and sizes, drawn from the museum's own
collections, are crammed into the already cramped galleries
with very little explanation as to the rhyme or reason behind
their choice or their arrangement. This is more than a little
bit confusing, but it also has the great virtue of letting
the objects speak for themselves without being overwhelmed by
extravagant interpretations.
   Although the show is not organized in a particularly
thoughtful way, it has some charming, clever and even moving
moments. In one gallery, a grippingly realistic 1943 Ben
Shahn poster announcing "This Is Nazi Brutality" is set next
to Jacques Lipchitz's semi-abstract drawing of the "Rape of
Europa." Nearby are Edward Hopper's desolate 1940 roadside
scene called "Gas" and Pablo Picasso's allegorical "Charnel
House" of 1945 -- pictures that evoke the lingering
Depression mentality of the beginning of the decade and the
extraordinary world-wide convulsions that occurred during its
first five years. But just a little further along is a
leading candidate for the booby prize as Worst Museum
Installation of the Year: 17 colorful plates from Matisse's
1947 illustrated book "Jazz" arranged as decorations around a
doorway]
   One of the most impressive things about this show is its
indication of just how much art this particular aunt has in
her storage vaults and rarely shows to visitors. Artists like
Honore Sharrer, Morris Hirshfield, Rico Lebrun, Alton Pickens
and Salvatore Fiume are not exactly familiar names, even
among regular museumgoers, and it is nice to have an
opportunity to see their work in relation to their
better-known contemporaries. (One also can't help but be
impressed by how assiduously MoMA followed contemporary art
back then; many of the works shown were acquired within a
year or two of their creation.)
   But in the end, the choice of artists is also a mixed bag.
For along with some interesting resurrections (and, alas,
some rather awkward disinterments), there are also some
amazing omissions. Picasso, Matisse and Miro are included;
but Stuart Davis, Georges Braque and Hans Arp -- all of whom
were particularly influential during the '40s -- are
inexplicably left out. Some major artists, such as David
Smith, are represented by surprisingly minor works that give
very little sense of their importance at the time.
   The rationale behind the mixture of "high art" and objects
from everyday life also remains unclear. Is this show
supposed to be primarily an artistic portrait of the decade,
or a social one, or both? And if the social element is
supposed to be of real importance, why is no attention given
to what must have been the most influential source of imagery
in America during the 1940s, Life magazine?
   In the latter half of the show, where the installation
focuses increasingly on paintings, familiar names prevail and
there is an increasing unity of pictorial thought. In fact,
the last few galleries, which are dominated by American
abstract artists, constitute a kind of picture essay about
the triumph of American abstract painting toward the end of
the decade. The gathering of major works that the museum
collected -- by artists such as Robert Motherwell, Jackson
Pollock, Willem DeKooning, Mark Rothko and Clyfford Still --
remains very impressive and reflects a unity of purpose that
is not always apparent in the earlier galleries.
   This in itself gives one food for thought. In recent years
there has been a lot of talk about "the new pluralism" in
art, in which virtually any kind of imagery is permissible
and no single style dominates. In fact, as this show makes
clear, the new pluralism is really not new at all.
   Nor should we think it started in the 1940s. Pluralism, it
seems to me, is one of the characteristic conditions of
artistic expression in the modern world. It is not that the
variety of artistic expression has increased so much in
recent years, but that critical thinking has become less
partisan and less focused. This, in turn, seems to be a
reflection of new marketing strategies for art, in which
diversification has come to be seen as a better bet than a
narrowly held position. Pluralism has long been present in
modern art -- even the impressionists represented only a
small corner of late 19th-century painting and were
themselves a rather diverse lot. Until recently, however, the
strategies of criticism and of the market emphasized what
were held to be dominant styles, and this flattened out our
perception of what was actually being produced at a given
moment.
   In fact, if "Art of the Forties" makes us aware of just
how pluralistic that decade was, it is in no small measure
because so many of the works in it are usually consigned to
storage. One of the most stimulating aspects of this show is
the direct result of its lack of focus, which invites us to
see beyond the narrow categories into which so much recent
art has been squeezed. Despite its faults, this backward look
at the decade that brought us to midcentury may provide us
with some valuable insights about the decade that will bring
us to its end.
   The exhibition, which is accompanied by an extensive
program of American and European films of the 1940s, will be
on view until April 30.
